We’ll compute each ratio step‐by‐step.

1. Operating Cash Flow Ratio 
 • Formula: Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities / Total Current Liabilities  
 • From the cash flow statement: Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities = –4,398,760.38  
 • From the balance sheet: Total Current Liabilities = 2,491,297.55  
 • Ratio = –4,398,760.38 / 2,491,297.55 ≈ –1.76

2. Cash Flow to Debt Ratio  
 • For this task (as in the sample) we use the same denominator (current liabilities).  
 • Ratio = –4,398,760.38 / 2,491,297.55 ≈ –1.76

3. Inventory Turnover Ratio  
 • Formula: Cost of Goods Sold / Average Inventory  
 • Cost of Goods Sold (income statement) = 6,290,000.00  
 • Inventory on 2024-01-30 = 3,540,000.00 and beginning inventory = 0.  
 • Average Inventory = (0 + 3,540,000.00) / 2 = 1,770,000.00  
 • Ratio = 6,290,000.00 / 1,770,000.00 ≈ 3.55

4. Debt to Equity Ratio  
 • Formula: Total Liabilities / Total Owner’s Equity  
 • Here total liabilities (from the balance sheet) = 2,491,297.55  
 • Total Owner’s Equity = 11,598,563.11  
 • Ratio = 2,491,297.55 / 11,598,563.11 ≈ 0.21

5. Quick Ratio  
 • Formula: (Current Assets – Inventory) / Current Liabilities  
 • Current Assets (end) = 8,810,936.45  
 • Inventory = 3,540,000.00  
 • Numerator = 8,810,936.45 – 3,540,000.00 = 5,270,936.45  
 • Ratio = 5,270,936.45 / 2,491,297.55 ≈ 2.12

6. Current Ratio  
 • Formula: Current Assets / Current Liabilities  
 • Ratio = 8,810,936.45 / 2,491,297.55 ≈ 3.54
